## Plan

**Approach:** Extract the rule logic (not the error formatting) into pure exported predicates in `runmanifest`, the package that already owns the canonical rules and that `cli` already imports (`runmanifest` does NOT import `cli`, so no cycle). Add two pure, IO-free functions — `IsValidIdentifier(value string) bool` (the `[A-Za-z0-9_.-]`, non-empty charset) and `IsValidRunID(value string) bool` (identifier charset PLUS the extra rules: leading/trailing dot, "..", all-dots, ".lock"). Rewrite both consumers to call these predicates while KEEPING their existing error formatting verbatim, because the two layers must produce different error text:
- runmanifest `validateRunID`/`validateIdentifier` keep wrapping with `ErrInvalidManifest` ("invalid manifest: invalid run id %q").
- cli `validateRunIDExtra` and capture `validateCLIIdentifier` keep the unwrapped form `invalid run id %q` / `invalid %s %q` — this exact text is contract: documented in docs/run.md ("Invalid ids produce `invalid run id \"<id>\"`") and asserted by TestRunShowInvalidRunIDBeforeGit and TestCaptureRejectsInvalidInputs.
This kills the drift risk (rules live once) while preserving every byte of observable behavior.

**Rule equivalence confirmed (behavior-preserving):** run.go:138-140 and manifest.go:314-316 are byte-identical extra-rule expressions; capture.go:278 and manifest.go:327 are byte-identical charsets. The ONLY existing divergence is error wrapping/text (above), which the plan preserves deliberately. Purity confirmed: both runmanifest funcs use only `strings`+`fmt`, no git/IO — safe to call before any git call (the BeforeGit test runs in a non-repo dir).

**Scope note (asymmetry to preserve):** `run show` validates the run id EAGERLY before touching git. `capture` does NOT eagerly validate the run id charset/extra-rules in the CLI layer — it only checks non-empty, then the full rule check happens later inside `runmanifest.Writer.Write -> Manifest.Validate -> validateRunID`. Do NOT add an eager run-id gate to capture; that would change timing/behavior. capture only shares the identifier predicate (for stage/ref-key).

**Files:**
- internal/runmanifest/manifest.go - add exported pure `IsValidIdentifier` and `IsValidRunID`; refactor unexported `validateIdentifier`/`validateRunID` to call them (keeping `ErrInvalidManifest` wrapping).
- internal/cli/run.go - rewrite `validateRunIDExtra` to call `runmanifest.IsValidRunID` (or keep the eager pre-git call but delegate the rule). Note: `validateCLIIdentifier("run id", id)` is still called first; consider collapsing both cli run-id checks into one delegating call to `runmanifest.IsValidRunID` while keeping the `invalid run id %q` message. Preserve the unwrapped error text exactly.
- internal/cli/capture.go - rewrite `validateCLIIdentifier` body to delegate the charset to `runmanifest.IsValidIdentifier`, keeping the unwrapped `is required` / `invalid %s %q` messages and its callers (stage, ref key) unchanged.

**Out of scope (noted, not touched):** internal/workflow/workflow.go `isIdentChar` is a THIRD copy of the identifier charset (self-documented as "reimplemented locally"). workflow neither imports nor is imported by runmanifest, so it could safely adopt `runmanifest.IsValidIdentifier` later, but that is outside this bead. init.go/artifactstore/role-token validators are different rule sets — leave alone.

**Tests:**
- TestRunShowInvalidRunIDBeforeGit must still pass unchanged (all 6 cases: slash, "..", ".lock", leading/trailing dot, all-dots), proving pre-git validation and the `invalid run id` text survive.
- TestCaptureRejectsInvalidInputs (invalid stage / invalid ref key text) must still pass.
- Add runmanifest unit table-test for `IsValidRunID`/`IsValidIdentifier` enumerating accept/reject cases (valid: "run-1", "a.b", "x_y"; reject: "", "bad/id", "..", "...", ".x", "x.", "x.lock", control/unicode chars).
- Optional anti-drift test: assert the cli copies are gone (e.g. cli delegates to runmanifest) — simplest is that the shared predicate is the single rule owner; a focused unit test on the exported funcs plus the surviving cli/runmanifest behavior tests is sufficient.

**Docs:** No doc change needed. docs/run.md (run-id rules + "validated before any git call" + `invalid run id "<id>"`) and docs/capture.md (`refs/etude/runs/<run-id>`, role charset) stay accurate because rules and error text are unchanged by design. Confirmed by re-reading both files.

**Risks:** Low. Main hazard is accidentally changing CLI error text/wrapping (would break the documented contract + tests) or accidentally adding eager run-id validation to capture (behavior/timing change). Mitigated by keeping per-layer error formatting and leaving cap/run validation call sites semantically identical. No import cycle (cli->runmanifest only). No git/IO in shared helpers.

